# Fluff Date: 2026-02-16 11:04:06
overview:<p>The Commando was first tested in 2463 by the Coventry Defense Conglomerate as one of the Lyran Commonwealth's earliest homegrown BattleMech designs. Engineer Andre Barcalow created a light, fast machine suited for reconnaissance and raiding. The primitive COM-1A, armed with a single Odin heavy laser, proved its worth at the Battle of Nox in 2475 by destroying heavier Kuritan Gladiators in the first large-scale BattleMech engagement.</p><p>Critical cooling flaws exposed during the "Long March" campaign led to the sophisticated COM-2D variant in 2486, which transformed the Commando into a deadly striker that has remained in continuous production for six centuries. The Lyran Commonwealth jealously guarded the design until the Amaris Civil War scattered examples across the Inner Sphere.</p>

capabilities:<p>The standard COM-2D Commando mounts paired short-range missile launchers providing ten tubes of firepower, complemented by an arm-mounted medium laser. This armament allows the twenty-five ton 'Mech to deliver devastating barrages effective against even assault-class machines when deployed in groups. The dual missile system prevents a single lucky hit from disabling all offensive capability, and pilots can concentrate fire on one target or split between two.</p><p>This firepower comes at significant cost. Each launcher draws from its own ammunition bin and cannot share reserves, meaning the Commando often exhausts its missiles within minutes of sustained combat. The four tons of armor equals that of lighter scouts, creating fatal vulnerability against heavier opponents. Without jump jets, the design struggles to disengage in rough terrain and cannot escape determined pursuit by larger 'Mechs.</p><p>The Commando excels in hit-and-run strikes, scouting in pairs to pin down enemy reconnaissance units, and rapid flanking maneuvers. Against the Draconis Combine's Panther, however, that heavier machine's superior range and jump capability proved an effective counter to Commando hunter-killer groups.</p>

deployment:<p>The Marian Hegemony's contribution to the Commando family replaces the standard missile systems with twin medium lasers in the left arm and double 15-rack rocket launchers mounted in the right arm and both side torsos. This configuration trades the reloadable SRM systems for devastating one-shot alpha strikes. Hansen's Roughriders clashed frequently with Taurian 4H variants during their campaign against the Concordat, finding that once the Marian-pattern machines exhausted their rockets, they became easy prey for energy-weapon-equipped opponents.</p>

history:<p>The Commando's development was driven by desperation. After Operation Prometheus gave the Lyran Commonwealth stolen Terran Hegemony BattleMech technology in 2455, Kurita raiders struck Coventry in 2461 and secured enough data to jumpstart the Combine's own program. The following year, disgruntled Alarion workers defected to the Free Worlds League with additional plans. Knowing its enemies would soon field their own 'Mechs, the Commonwealth rushed the COM-1A into service in 2463, followed by the definitive COM-2D in 2486 after the original's cooling problems proved insurmountable.</p><p>The Commando became a cornerstone of Lyran reconnaissance forces and remained exclusively Commonwealth property for centuries. The Star League attempted repeatedly to acquire the design, but Lyran officials employed clever stalling and subtle deception to keep it from foreign hands. This changed during the Amaris Civil War when Lyran volunteers, disaffected by their government's neutrality, brought Commandos into Star League service with the Loyalist forces that liberated Terra. Some of these 'Mechs accompanied General Kerensky into exile, eventually becoming the basis for the Clan Commando IIC.</p><p>The Succession Wars spread the Commando throughout the Inner Sphere as mercenary units acquired examples and developed numerous field modifications. These "dash-seven" variants emerged from refit bays across known space, with Mech-it-Lube franchises becoming particularly associated with Commando modifications. The creation of the Federated Commonwealth finally broke the Lyran monopoly, making the Commando the standard light 'Mech alongside the Valkyrie. Vandenberg Mechanized Industries received license to produce the COM-2D for the Taurian Defense Force, while the Marian Hegemony developed its own rocket-armed COM-4H variant.</p><p>Task Force Serpent's campaign against Huntress in 3060 saw extensive use of upgraded dash-seven variants, prompting Coventry Metal Works to dedicate factory space for official recreations of these successful field modifications. The Word of Blake's occupation of Coventry from 3068 to 3074 resulted in the COM-7B variant optimized for hunting Lyran resistance fighters, including the Bradford family forces that continued to defy Blakist rule. The technological recovery of the thirty-first and thirty-second centuries brought further refinements, including the C3-equipped COM-8S spotter and the paradigm-shifting COM-9S long-range harasser.</p>

